<reference id="manpages">
 <title>Options and Configuration</title>

 <!-- Startup Script -->

 <refentry id="man-regina">
  <refmeta>
   <refentrytitle>regina</refentrytitle>
   <manvolnum>1</manvolnum>
  </refmeta>

  <refnamediv>
   <refname>regina</refname>
   <refname>regina.bat</refname>
   <refpurpose>&regina; startup script</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>

  <refsynopsisdiv>
   <cmdsynopsis>
    <command>regina</command>
    <group>
     <arg><option>-q, --quiet</option></arg>
     <arg><option>-v, --verbose</option></arg>
    </group>
    <group>
     <arg><option>--gui</option></arg>
     <arg><option>--console</option></arg>
     <arg><option>--text</option></arg>
    </group>
    <group>
     <arg><option>--jni</option></arg>
    </group>
    <arg><option>--jnilibname=</option><replaceable>name</replaceable></arg>
    <arg rep=repeat><replaceable>file</replaceable></arg>
   </cmdsynopsis>
  </refsynopsisdiv>

  <refsect1>
   <title>Description</title>
   &regabstract;
   <para>
    On some systems &regina; is installed as
    <filename>/usr/bin/regina-normal</filename> so as not to conflict
    with the <application>Regina</application> <acronym>REXX</acronym>
    interpreter.
   </para>
   <para>
    &linux; users should start &regina; by running the
    <filename>regina</filename> startup script in the main
    &regina; directory.  &windows; users may either start a
    &cygwin; <filename>bash</filename> shell and run this same
    startup script, or may run <filename>regina.bat</filename>
    from their usual &windows; environment.
   </para>
   <para>
    Any files specified on the command-line will be opened on startup.
   </para>
   <para>
    When passing files to open, &windows; users cannot use absolute
    filenames in &cygwin; format (such as
    <filename>/home/sam/file.rga</filename>).  You will need to use
    either absolute pathnames in &windows; format (such as
    <filename>c:\my\data\file.rga</filename>) or relative pathnames
    (such as <filename>data/file.rga</filename> or
    <filename>data\file.rga</filename>).  This constraint does not apply
    to &linux; users.
   </para>
   <warning><para>
    When passing command-line arguments, avoid using characters that have
    a special meaning to <filename>bash</filename>
    (such as quotes, brackets, backslashes and
    the like).  You should <emphasis>only</emphasis> use the arguments
    described below.  Using special characters in command-line arguments
    can have unpredictable results, and may in the worst case result in
    data loss (although I've tried to make the scripts foolproof enough
    to prevent this).  This warning applies to &windows;
    users too, since <filename>regina.bat</filename> passes its
    command-line arguments straight through to the
    <filename>bash</filename> startup script.
   </para></warning>
  </refsect1>

  <refsect1>
   <title>Options</title>
   <variablelist>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><option>-q</option></term>
     <term><option>--quiet</option></term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       Start in quiet mode.  No output will be produced except
       for errors.
      </para>
      <para>
       This is equivalent to setting configuration option
       <parameter>REGINA_VERBOSITY</parameter>=<literal>0</literal>.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><option>-v</option></term>
     <term><option>--verbose</option></term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       Start in verbose mode.  Lots of diagnostic
       information will be output.
      </para>
      <para>
       This is equivalent to setting configuration option
       <parameter>REGINA_VERBOSITY</parameter>=<literal>2</literal>.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><option>--gui</option> (default)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>Run with the full GUI.</para>
      <para>
       This is equivalent to setting configuration option
       <parameter>REGINA_INTERFACE</parameter>=<literal>gui</literal>.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><option>--console</option></term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       Run as a graphical &jython; console, without loading the full GUI.
      </para>
      <para>
       This is equivalent to setting configuration option
       <parameter>REGINA_INTERFACE</parameter>=<literal>console</literal>.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><option>--text</option></term>
     <listitem>
      <para>Run as a text &jython; console, with no GUI whatsoever.</para>
      <para>
       This is equivalent to setting configuration option
       <parameter>REGINA_INTERFACE</parameter>=<literal>text</literal>.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><option>--jni</option> (default)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       Access the C++ calculation engine as a shared library using &jni;.
      </para>
      <para>
       This is equivalent to setting configuration option
       <parameter>REGINA_ENGINE</parameter>=<literal>jni</literal>.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><option>--jnilibname=</option><replaceable>name</replaceable>
      (default = <literal>regina-engine-jni</literal>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       Use <replaceable>name</replaceable> as the name of the
       &jni; calculation engine library to load.  This should
       be the platform-independent library name, so the
       library will in fact be called
       <filename>lib<replaceable>name</replaceable>.so</filename> for
       &linux; users or
       <filename><replaceable>name</replaceable>.dll</filename> for
       &windows; users.
      </para>
      <para>
       This option is only relevant when using &jni; engine access
       (see option <option>--jni</option> for details) and is equivalent
       to setting configuration option <parameter>REGINA_JNIENGINE</parameter>.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
   </variablelist>
  </refsect1>

  <refsect1>
   <title>Environment Variables</title>
   <para>
    All of the options described in the
    <link linkend="man-regina.conf">configuration reference</link> can
    be set as environment variables.  Of particular interest are
    <envar>REGINA_OPTIONS_GLOBAL</envar> and
    <envar>REGINA_OPTIONS_LOCAL</envar> which specify the directories
    containing the configuration files.
   </para>
  </refsect1>

