 <!-- Configuration -->

 <refentry id="man-regina.conf">
  <refmeta>
   <refentrytitle>regina.conf</refentrytitle>
   <manvolnum>5</manvolnum>
  </refmeta>

  <refnamediv>
   <refname>regina.conf</refname>
   <refpurpose>&regina; configuration</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>

  <refsect1>
   <title>Description</title>
   <para>
    When running &regina; using the standard startup script, you can
    configure its behaviour in many ways.  The configuration consists of
    a number of options, each of which may be given a value.
   </para>
   <para>
    The methods by which you may set these options are (in decreasing
    order of priority):
    <itemizedlist>
     <listitem><para>
      Command-line options to the startup script.  See the
      <link linkend="man-regina">startup script reference</link> for
      further details.
     </para></listitem>
     <listitem><para>
      The local configuration file:
      <filename>~/.regina/regina.conf</filename>
     </para></listitem>
     <listitem><para>
      The global configuration file:
      <filename>/etc/regina/regina.conf</filename> (or
      <filename><replaceable>REGINA_HOME</replaceable>/regina.conf</filename>
      if directory <filename>/etc/regina</filename> does not exist)
     </para></listitem>
     <listitem><para>
      Environment variables.  For instance, you might have environment
      variable <envar>REGINA_ENGINE</envar> with the value
      <literal>jni</literal>.
     </para></listitem>
    </itemizedlist>
   </para>
   <para>
    Any option set by a method lower in this list will be
    overridden by the same option set higher in the list (for instance,
    a command-line option will override a setting in the local
    configuration file).
   </para>
   <para>
    On some systems the global configuration file is installed as
    <filename>/etc/regina-normal/regina.conf</filename> so as not to
    conflict with the <application>Regina</application>
    <acronym>REXX</acronym> interpreter.
   </para>
   <para>
    The local and global configuration files should each contain
    lines of the form:
    <screen>
    <replaceable>option</replaceable>=<replaceable>value</replaceable>
    </screen>
    Blank lines or lines beginning with a hash (<literal>#</literal>)
    are ignored.
   </para>
   <para>
    Environment variables <envar>REGINA_OPTIONS_GLOBAL</envar> and
    <envar>REGINA_OPTIONS_LOCAL</envar> can be used to change the
    location of the global and local configuration files; see the
    Options section below for details.
   </para>
  </refsect1>

  <refsect1>
   <title>Options</title>
   <para>The configuration options that can be set are as follows.</para>
   <variablelist>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><parameter>REGINA_VERBOSITY</parameter>
      (default = <literal>1</literal>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       The verbosity level for the startup script.
       For this option only, a setting in the configuration file(s) will
       clobber the command-line options <option>-q</option>,
       <option>--quiet</option>, <option>-v</option> and
       <option>--verbose</option>.
       </para>
       <para>
       Recognised values are:
       <variablelist>
        <varlistentry>
         <term><literal>0</literal></term>
         <listitem><para>
          Display errors only (quiet).
         </para></listitem>
        </varlistentry>
        <varlistentry>
         <term><literal>1</literal></term>
         <listitem><para>
          Display errors and warnings.
         </para></listitem>
        </varlistentry>
        <varlistentry>
         <term><literal>2</literal></term>
         <listitem><para>
          Display errors, warnings and diagnostic output (verbose).
         </para></listitem>
        </varlistentry>
       </variablelist>
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><parameter>REGINA_HOME</parameter></term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       The directory in which &regina; is installed.  This should be the
       directory containing the &regina; startup script, the
       <filename>scripts/</filename> subdirectory and so on.
       This defaults to the directory containing the startup script that
       was run.
      </para>
      <para>This option cannot be set in the configuration files.</para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><parameter>REGINA_OPTIONS_GLOBAL</parameter>
      (default = <filename>/etc/regina</filename>, but see below)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       The directory containing the global configuration file.
      </para>
      <para>
       Clearly this option cannot be set in the configuration files!
      </para>
      <para>
       This defaults to <filename>/etc/regina</filename>, or
       <filename><replaceable>REGINA_HOME</replaceable></filename> if
       directory <filename>/etc/regina</filename> does not exist.
      </para>
      <para>
       On some systems this defaults to
       <filename>/etc/regina-normal</filename> so as not to
       conflict with the <application>Regina</application>
       <acronym>REXX</acronym> interpreter.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><parameter>REGINA_OPTIONS_LOCAL</parameter>
      (default = <filename>~/.regina</filename>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       The directory containing the local configuration file.
      </para>
      <para>
       Clearly this option cannot be set in the configuration files!
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><parameter>REGINA_BTOOLS</parameter> (default =
      <filename><replaceable>REGINA_HOME</replaceable>/lib/btools.jar</filename>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       The location of the &btools; library.  &btools; is a set of
       &java; classes that are necessary for &regina; to run.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><parameter>REGINA_JYTHON</parameter> (default =
      <filename><replaceable>REGINA_HOME</replaceable>/lib/jython.jar</filename>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       The location of the &jython; library.  &jython; is optional, but
       is needed if you wish to <link linkend="jython-overview">write and run
       scripts</link> from within &regina;.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><parameter>REGINA_JAVAHELP</parameter> (default =
      <filename><replaceable>REGINA_HOME</replaceable>/lib/jh.jar</filename>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       The location of the &javahelp; library.  &javahelp; is optional,
       but is needed if you wish to use the embedded help browser.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry id="REGINA-EXTRA-CLASSES">
     <term><parameter>REGINA_EXTRA_CLASSES</parameter>
      (default = empty)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       Any other &java; classes that need to be added to the classpath
       before &regina; is run.  Typically you will not need to put
       anything here.
      </para>
      <para>
       If you do need to use this option, it should be set to a series
       of jars and/or directories separated by the standard classpath
       separator (a colon under &linux; or a semicolon under &windows;).
       An example is:
       <literal>/usr/share/java/foo.jar:/home/bab/lib/</literal>
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><parameter>REGINA_JAVA</parameter></term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       The command used to start &java;.  If the command
       <command>java</command> can be found on the path then this option
       defaults to the full path of that command
       (such as <command>/usr/bin/java</command>).
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry id="REGINA-JNIDIR">
     <term><parameter>REGINA_JNIDIR</parameter> (default =
      <filename><replaceable>REGINA_HOME</replaceable>/bin:/usr/lib</filename>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       A colon-separated list of directories containing &jni; libraries.
       If you wish to connect to the calculation engine using &jni;, one
       of these directories must contain the &jni; calculation engine
       library (see the option
       <parameter>REGINA_ENGINE</parameter> for further details).
      </para>
      <para>
       The &jni; calculation engine library itself will usually be called
       <filename>libregina-engine-jni.so</filename> on &linux; systems
       or <filename>regina-engine-jni.dll</filename> on &windows;
       systems, but this can be changed by setting option
       <parameter>REGINA_JNIENGINE</parameter>.
      </para>
      <para>
       Note that option <parameter>REGINA_JNIDIR</parameter> should only
       provide a list of directories, not actual library names.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><parameter>REGINA_JARDIR</parameter> (default =
      <filename><replaceable>REGINA_HOME</replaceable>/bin</filename>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       The directory containing the &regina; user interface jars.
       This directory should contain <filename>regina.jar</filename> as
       well as other optional jars such as
       <filename>regina-docs.jar</filename>.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><parameter>REGINA_CACHEDIR</parameter> (default =
      <filename><replaceable>REGINA_OPTIONS_LOCAL</replaceable>/cache</filename>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       The &jython; cache directory, to be used by &jython; to store
       temporary package cache files.  This should be a directory to
       which you have write access.
      </para>
      <para>
       A value for <parameter>python.cachedir</parameter> in the
       general &jython; registry file(s) will override this option.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><parameter>REGINA_ENGINE</parameter>
      (default = <literal>jni</literal>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       Specifies how the C++ calculation engine will be accessed.
       Recognised values are:
       <variablelist>
        <varlistentry>
         <term><literal>jni</literal></term>
         <listitem><para>
          The engine will be accessed as a shared library using &jni;.
         </para></listitem>
        </varlistentry>
       </variablelist>
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><parameter>REGINA_INTERFACE</parameter>
      (default = <literal>gui</literal>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       Specifies which style of interface to use when running
       &regina;.  Recognised values are:
       <variablelist>
        <varlistentry>
         <term><literal>gui</literal></term>
         <listitem><para>
          Run the full &regina; GUI.
         </para></listitem>
        </varlistentry>
        <varlistentry>
         <term><literal>console</literal></term>
         <listitem><para>
          Run as a graphical &jython; console, without loading the full GUI.
         </para></listitem>
        </varlistentry>
        <varlistentry>
         <term><literal>text</literal></term>
         <listitem><para>
          Run as a text &jython; console, with no GUI whatsoever.
         </para></listitem>
        </varlistentry>
       </variablelist>
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><parameter>REGINA_JNIENGINE</parameter>
      (default = <literal>regina-engine-jni</literal>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       The name of the &jni; calculation engine library to load.
       This should be the platform-independent library name, so if this
       option has value <literal>foo</literal> then the library will in
       fact be called <filename>libfoo.so</filename> for &linux; users or
       <filename>foo.dll</filename> for &windows; users.
      </para>
      <para>
       This option is only relevant when using &jni; engine access
       (see option <parameter>REGINA_ENGINE</parameter> for details).
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
   </variablelist>
  </refsect1>

